In response to the message sent  Mon, 18 Aug 86 13:18:39 PDT from nowicki@Sun.COM 

The RNAME specification was intended to follow the same specification
for mail destinations as was suggested for mailboxes, see page 53.
In terms of the master file, Mockapetris@B.ISI.EDU is Mockapetris.B.ISI.EDU.

The scheme there us that if a mail address is X@Y, X is encoded as a
single label (regardless of the characters it contains), and Y is broken
into separate labels at dots.  The reason was so you can separate the
local part from the global part (i.e. X and Y).  The theory behind this
was that you might see mailbox level binding on top of agent binding (as
in MX).  The only restriction that might cause a problem is that then
the local part is limited to 63 characters, but some thought that was a
good direction for natural selection in mail addressing anyway.

paul
